  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Awareness-raising through Media Sens.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project will engage Burundian youth between the ages of 15 and 35 in a process that aims to foster multiple truths and inclusive memorialisation towards the non-recurrence of violence along ethnic lines. By stimulating a decentralised intergenerational dialogue to promote multiple truths, it therefore aims to challenge collective ethnic memories using an innovative approach to research, capacity-building and awareness-raising that is yet to be done in Burundi. Societal and cultural factors such as the culture of silence, intense respect for elders and unquestioning respect for authority will be examined, especially the manner that they contributeto polarising memorialisation processes. Moreover, by engaging the media and utilising audio-visual materials, the project will tackle the criticism of the media#s role in accepting #tribal hatreds#. In Burundi, the unique role and strength of the media will be harnessed to ensure the presentation of more accurate, pluralistic memories and interpretations of the past.

The project will provide rural Burundians with space to express themselves and will build on previous initiatives to raise the awareness of the population on dealing with the past, using an innovative, interactive methodology. All of the findings and recommendations from the research will be transformed into audio materials to be used for such awareness-raising. Finally, comparative research recommendations will be given to national and international decision-makers. These recommendations will in particular address parallel and complementary approaches to truth-telling, looking beyond the anticipated limitations of institutionalised truth-telling at the TRC.</narrative>
  </description>
  <participating-org role="4" type="24">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Association Ijambo</narrative>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Radio Isanganiro is a new partner organisation of Oxfam Novib. It is a well known radio channel in Burundi, which is reaching people in Burundi, but also in neighbouring countries Rwanda, Tanzania, DRC, and even the diaspora through internet. It contributes to dialogue on peace and reconciliation.
The radio channel has a director and journalists, technical personnel, commercial officer, etc.
The contract partner is association Ijambo, which is the judicial entity that is responsible for the radio. Apart from the staff working for the radio itself, there are an executive committee and an overlooking committee that have just been recently renewed.
Thereis a good mix of men and women (about one third are women) and different ethnicities (Hutu, Tutsi, Twa) working for the radio and in the executive committee and the overlooking committee.</narrative>
  </participating-org>
